              "text": "The Indian Ocean has fed the Digo people for as long as they have inhabited the coast. Long before the spice trade brought cardamom and turmeric to their kitchens, before rice cultivation transformed their agriculture, before Islam reshaped their spiritual life, the ocean was there — providing protein, shaping daily rhythms, and connecting the Digo to a maritime world that stretches from Mozambique to the Arabian Peninsula. Artisanal fishing remains the primary source of marine protein for coastal Digo communities, and the relationship between the fisherman, his vessel, and the sea is one of the foundational narratives of coastal identity."
