              "text": "The structural skeleton of a Digo house is made from boriti — mangrove poles, typically ten to twelve feet long, harvested from the dense mangrove forests that grow along the tidal waterways of the south coast. Mangrove wood is prized for construction because it is naturally resistant to termites and rot, two forces that destroy lesser timbers within a few seasons in the coastal climate. The poles are straight, strong, and remarkably uniform in diameter, making them ideal for framing."
