              "text": "When two Digo people meet for the first time, the conversation follows a predictable path to a single question: *\"Wa atu ani?\"* — \"Whose people are you?\" The answer is not a family name in the Western sense. It is the name of a *fuko* — a matrilineal clan passed from mother to child across uncounted generations. The fuko is the first and deepest layer of Digo identity, the kinship structure through which a person knows who they are, who they belong to, and what obligations bind them to the wider community."
